# Confidence: No public PoC known — pattern inferred from the
# CVE/advisory description only. The CVE describes an integer overflow
# via improper input validation in Windows Terminal, exploitable remotely
# over the network [1][2]. No specific protocol framing, payload bytes,
# or wire-format details are available from the advisory [2] (the MSRC
# page failed to render actionable technical content). The match below
# targets anomalously large TCP payloads toward Windows Terminal's default
# SSH/connection-broker port (2222) as a heuristic for oversized input
# that may trigger the integer overflow — this is a LOW-CONFIDENCE
# behavioural proxy, not a verified exploit signature.
# No packet-capture (PCAP) data source is available to this pipeline —
# this pattern is NOT verified against captured exploit traffic.
# ANALYST REVIEW REQUIRED before any deployment. Tune port and dsize
# thresholds to match your environment's Windows Terminal listener config.
# NOTE: CVE-2026-59117 is 3 days old [1]; advisory detail is minimal and
# no CISA KEV entry is present at time of generation.
alert tcp $EXTERNAL_NET any -> $HOME_NET 2222 (
  msg:"THREATFORGE CVE-2026-59117 Windows Terminal integer overflow RCE attempt";
  flow:established,to_server; dsize:>65000;
  threshold:type both, track by_src, count 3, seconds 10;
  reference:cve,2026-59117;
  metadata:mitre_technique_id T1190, is_kev false, status experimental;
  classtype:attempted-admin; sid:9000104; rev:1; )

